@node contrib " How to conribute to A.F"
If you wish to contribute anything such as:

Letters
Pictures
Adverts
Articles
Points of View

then write to the usual address:

Mark Seddon(A.F)
49 Rosslyn Drive
Moreton
Wirral
L46 OSU

Please, please send us your points of view, we'd love to hear
them.

We receive loads of adverts each month, so make sure you get them
in early. They can be saved as ASCII or as a 16 colour (MAX) picture.
If you send an advert in on paper, make sure it is NOT drawn, keep
it brief and in plain text. 
In some circumstances, we can offer hand-scanning or flatbed scanning
of adverts but for 100% inclusion in A.F send your text or pic on a disk.

Thanx! Editor of A.F
@endnode


@node release "Information about A.F release dates:"


Frontier is available during the last week of each month........
Amiga Frontier IS released monthly. Loads of people keep writing
in and asking for A.F and they always say, surely A.F can't be out
monthly, it must slip back two or three weeks.

Well, it doesn't.
Three versions of A.F are released every month.
The first is usually released about 1 or 2 days after planned
release date, but never anywhere near a week!
Release number 1 is sent out to Online P.D Wallasey
(this version is called `A')

The second release of A.F normally comes out a day after number 1.
It features the same articles, but with more time spent on checking
articles for spelling errors, punctuation, grammar etc...
This is sent to readers all over the country who requested a copy of
A.F.
Basically, anyone who receives A.F directly from us receives the second
version
(this version is called `B')

The third release is for the local computer clubs and P.D libraries
all over the country (excluding Online P.D) 
This version is severely tested and editing and tested and edited
and tested and edited, get the picture?
Final release 3 gets released about 3 days after number 2.
(this, the final version is `C')


Why do we do it? Because I like to spend time perfecting each
issue, but I don't want to hold all issues back so that they are
released every 5 weeks. Anyway, the first version isn't bad is it?

To find out which version you have, check out the version page
in this Amigaguide file (from the main contents menu).

@endnode


